        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>&ldquo;We are not doing this just to save money,&rdquo; Kim said. &ldquo;The most important concern that we have is student learning.&rdquo;</p>
<p>He added that the hybrid program has been largely successful&mdash;hybrid students outperformed their peers in traditional courses in the reading and writing components, but there was a decrease in hybrid students&rsquo; oral scores. Although traditional students&rsquo; oral scores averaged 83.5 percent, the students in the hybrid version averaged 81.1 percent.</p>
<p>Amy Wentworth, a lecturing fellow in Spanish at Duke, said she is &ldquo;old-fashioned&rdquo; and prefers face-to-face interactions between professors and students.</p>
<p>&ldquo;If the students are just sitting there listening to the teacher or just sitting there watching the video, they&rsquo;re not performing,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;It is so important to actually do something, to perform, to take something on as one&rsquo;s own, to claim it. Basically, even in Spanish 1, a student has to claim Spanish as their own.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Duke junior Wes Norris, who is enrolled in Spanish 1, said taking beginner Spanish online would make the course appealing to students just looking to fill their schedules.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I think that would be blatantly retarded,&rdquo; Norris said. &ldquo;If you&rsquo;re doing it entirely online, you&rsquo;re going to have no interaction with people, and the entire purpose of language is to interact with people.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The reasons for the creation of online courses go beyond mere budget cuts, but Hoover said that if UNC wants to save money, it can do so through other means. For example, UNC students are required to take a lifetime fitness course, which Hoover said could easily go online.</p>
<p>Duke plans to cut its operating budget by $125 million over the next three years, but administrators said the University has no plans to move any of its courses online.</p>

